history.content:
Yes, 61c. I think if you don't have much practical software engineering experience, CS 169 or 160 could be very useful.

186 doesn't strictly requires 61c, but I think it's a good idea to take 61c before it. 189 is interesting and you'll want to take it some day, but it's kind of niche (e.g. if you're interested in research)

children.subject: 61c, then 162. They are the cs classes that you have not yet taken and I consider as most important.
I actually don't know much UI design so was thinking about taking 160 to learn it. Would you not recommend that?

Could you clarify on "a lot of annoying, busy work, for very little reward"?
I'm considering taking this class next semester and would like all the insight I can get!

61C for sure. If you want to pair 61C with something else, then I think 186 is the easiest out of all of them. It doesn't really require 61C. There's some stuff about disks and I/Os which are introduced in 61C, but it's very easy to pick it up on the spot.

189 is cool if you want to do ML and Shewchuk is teaching it next semester. He's pretty good and I definitely enjoyed the class when I took it last Spring when he taught it. 

Take 160 with a grain of salt. That class made me miserable my spring semester. It's a lot of annoying, busy work for very little reward, and if you're not good at UI design, you'll hate this class with every fiber of your being.

history.content: I have taken 61a, 61b, and 70. I am currently taking 170 and 188. I am wondering what other people would consider to be important cs classes to take as soon as possible. Right now I am thinking 61c and either 160 or 186 or 189. I don't really know what my specific interests in CS are yet. Any advice would be appreciate. Thanks
